column5: Fruit figure 8-shaped with upper half ribbed. Local name Ayote.
Fruits large, bottle-gourd shape, dark tan with few spots, 1.6kg. Local name Ayote.
Fruit small, round. Local name Ayote.
Fruit crook-neck shaped. Local name Ayote.
Warm, humid area. Fruits large, round, cream colored. Flesh about 3cm thick, dark orange. Seeds with deep brown margin. Local name Ayote.
Fruit 2.6kg, whitish, shaped like acorn squash. Received as Cucurbita sp.  Local name Ayote.
Fruit 2.8kg, long. Received as Cucurbita sp. Local name Ayote.
Good keeper, but flesh of poor quality
fruit flattened, 12 by 15in, buff with paler spots, deeply ribbed
Yellow, ribbed, oblate medium-sized; cooked and eaten as a vegetable
Fruit subelongate, 15 by 12in, buff, deeply ribbed
Fruit flattened, 15in across, heavily ribbed, pale-buff
Plants medium vigor, midseason variety leaf small; fruit 14in long with 6in bulb and 4in neck; light green, long, slender, smooth, curved neck; flesh orange; seed brown.
"Jack o'latern shaped", solid green at first maturing to an orange tan, fairly good table quality, large seed cavity, thin fruit walls.  Probably polymorphic.
Shows good resistance to powdery mildew.
Plants vigorous, midseason variety; fruit 22in long with 10in bulk and 8in neck, 10-20 grooves, tan netted, green, waxy; flesh 3in thick, orange. 3 large fruits per plant, often weighing over 100lbs.
Large Butternut Squash. Elongate cylindrical, curved, blossom end bulbous, 10cm diameter. Used for pies.
Flattened at blossom end and tapers gradually to stem end, weight 2kg, brownish orange.
Brittingham. Vine type. Fruit depressed globose, weight 2kg, brownish orange. Used for pies.
Vine trailing; fruit white, 10 to 20 pounds. Good table quality; good winter keeper.
Identifications by Dr. C. R. Gunn.
Fruit ovate, slightly ribbed, orange, 30cm diam., 30cm long.
Fruit ovoid, ribbed tan with buff mottling, 25cm diam., 20cm long.
Fruit flattened globose, slightly ribbed, warty, buff.
Fruit flattened-oblate, deeply ribbed at base, dark buff. Rind hard. Flesh  medium thick, light orange. Locally called Knoc kun (Cascara dura).
Fruits green, light green striped, yellow at maturity, pyriform with pronounced  neck, 23cm long, 15cm diam. Rind 1 mm thick. Flesh lemon yellow. Local name  Calabaza de Castilla.
Obtained from Moises Gomez. Fruit flattened ovoid, ribbed, buff. Rind hard.  Flesh thick, orange. Locally called Tockun.
Fruit bluntly obovate, shallow ribs, deep tan, 15cm long.
Fruits tan, large, oblong, slightly bell-shaped, 40cm long, 26cm diam. Rind 2mm  thick. Flesh deep orange. Local name Calabaza de Castilla.
Obtained from F. Cardenas R. Fruit pear shaped, 1.8kg. Seeds white with dark border.
Fruit large, ovoid, ribbed, light tan, mottled dark green. Rind very hard.  Seeds many, plump.
Fruit flat, many lobed, dull yellow. Eaten when young. Locally called Kanasin.
Fruit large, oblong, dark green; squash and seeds eaten
Obtained from Moises Gomez. Fruit ovoid, slightly ribbed, buff. Locally called  Tockun.
Seeds are roasted, shelled, and eaten
Fruit extremely flat, deeply lobed, dark buff, reticulated dark green. Flesh  thin, dark orange.
Fruit small, flat, ribbed, dark brown. Rind thin. Flesh medium thick, dark  orange.
Fruit oblate-flattened, ribbed, buff. Rind hard. Many seeded.
Fruit spherical, ribbed, light tan. Rind very hard.
Fruit dark green-skinned, with dark orange flesh, patty pan shaped. Seeds small, white with brown margins
Fruits tan, pyriform, 25cm long, 22cm diam. Rind 0.5mm thick. Placenta deep orange. Flesh lemon yellow. Local name Calabaza de Castilla.
Fruit spherical, slightly ribbed, orange-buff. Rind hard. Flesh thin, pale  orange.
Fruit club shaped, tan with dark green spots, 10cm diam., 28cm long.
Fruits light green, tan mottling, turban-shaped, 16m long, 25cm diam. Local  name Calabaza.
Fruits green, light green striped, turban-shaped, 16cm long, 20cm diam.
Fruit spindle shaped, light buff, 30cm diam., 64cm long.
Fruit long elliptic, shallow ribs, light buff, mottled tan and green,  20cm diam., 45cm long. Many seeds germinating. Locally called Tomala.
Fruits dark green, tan-striped, turban-shaped, 11cm long, 18cm diam. Local name  Calabaza.
Fruit long necked, 12cm diam. at widest part, 30cm long, orange buff, green  on neck.
Fruit small, deeply ribbed at stem end, apically dome-shaped, smooth, dark  orange buff, marked brown. Rind soft.
Obtained from Alfonso Lopez. Forage type.
Fruit flat, 10 lobed, 25cm diam., tan with dark green reticulations.
Fruits dark tan, black mottling, slight bloom, turban-shaped, 12cm long, 14cm  diam. Local name Calabaza.
Fruit flattened ovate, shallow ribs, white, 23cm diam.
Fruit ovoid, shallow ribs, white, 17cm diam., 23cm long. Flesh cream.
Vines. Fruits light tan, slightly green mottled, 16cm long, 18cm diam. Local name Calabasa.
Fruit short club shaped, ribbed, neck 11.5cm diam., 15cm long, body 23cm diam.,  13cm long.
Fruit large, curved, club-shaped, ribbed, pale tan, 15cm diam., 45cm long. Rind  hard. Flesh thin, dark orange.
Fruit globose, smooth, striped and reticulated dark green, 20cm long.
Fruit oblate, deeply lobed, warty, 25cm diam.
Fruits tan, dark green mottling, slight bloom, Canadian Crookneck shape, 31cm long, 13cm diam.
Fruits tan, dark green mottling, tan mottling at maturity, turban-shaped, 15.8  long, 20cm diam. Local name Calabaza criolla.
Fruits dark tan, ovate, 20cm long, 18.4cm diam. Local name Calabaza criolla.
Fruit elliptical, slightly ribbed, orange marked green, 28cm diam., 46cm long.
Fruit depressed globose, ribbed. Rind soft, mottled green and tan, 33cm diam.,  20cm long.
Fruits light green, tan mottling, turban-shaped, 23cm long, 22cm diam. Local  name Calabaza camotuda.
Fruits tan, flattened-round, warty, 14cm long, 19cm diam. Primitive type.
Fruits mottled green and tan, heavy bloom, top-shaped, 21cm long, 15cm diam.
Fruits tan, turban-shaped, 12cm long, 19cm diam. Local name Calabaza.
Fruits dark green, splotchy yellow at maturity, slight bloom, surface slightly  lumpy, pear-shaped, 23cm long, 24cm diam. Local name Calabaza.
Fruit obovate, faintly ribbed, nearly white, 15cm diam., 25cm long.
Two fruits, round, slightly flattened with shallow ribs, rind dark green with tan mottling.
Pepos purchased in market from woman from San Juan del Rio.
Fruits dark orange, dark green and tan mottled, bell-shaped, 16.7cm long, 13.2  cm diam. Local name Calabaza criolla.
Fruit flat, many lobes, dull yellow. Locally called Kanasin.
Fruit flat, ribbed, dark brown with heavy bloom. Rind soft, thick. Flesh dark orange.
Fruit depressed globose, ribbed. Rind rough, wrinkled dark buff, 25cm diam., 18 cm long.
Pepo obtained from Sr. Donaciano Cruz Reyes.  This calabasa is the more common of the two cultivated in this region and is preferred for its flesh.  N.V. Tamala

Pepo obtained from Sr. Sesilio Escobar Matus.  This is one of two commonly cultivated calabasas in this area.  This type matures in 2 months, the fruit is highly prized for consumption when the skin has hardened, prior to this time it is not worth eating.  The mature fruit color is beige, immature fruits may be white, green or green\white striped.  This type provides more fruit than tamalajota, the second typed cultivated in this area.
Pepos purchased in market from woman from San Juan del Rio.
Seed large. Local name Calabaza de Castilla.
Plants mature later and are less predictable than Cucurbita mixta. Sown in June and July, harvested in November. Cook mature fruit. Sample donated by Encornacion Torres Legarra.
Fruits dark green, tan markings, bell-shaped, 15cm long, 18cm diam. Local name  Calabasa.
Fruit obovate, oblong, ellipsoid, ovate or clavate 14-73cm long, 13-26.5cm wide. Some green, some warted. Flesh orange, 2.5-4cm thick. Rind soft-hard. Plant in June, harvest in December.
Fruits dark green, light green striped, slightly bell-shaped, 25.5cm long, 16  cm diam. Local name Calabaza.
Fruit flattened globose, deeply ribbed, buff, 20cm diam.
Fruits tan, pear-shaped, 28cm long, 15cm diam., cracks horizontally at maturity. Local name Calabaza.
Fruits spheroid, tapering toward top and bottom, 21cm long, 19cm diam. Local  name Calabaza.
Fruits tan, green striped, oblong, 22cm long, 15cm diam. Local name Calabaza.
Fruit depressed globose, ribbed. Rind hard, mottled tan and orange, 36cm wide,  20cm long.
Fruits deep orange, elongate, 32cm long, 12cm diam. Placenta greenish-brown. Flesh deep orange. Local name Calabaza criolla.
Fruits tan, dark green and tan mottled, turban-shaped, 15cm long, 22.7cm diam.  Placenta brown. Flesh greenish. Local name Calabaza criolla.
Fruits green with white stripes, bell-shaped, 21cm long, 17.5cm diam. Local name Calabaza de Castilla.
Seeds white with tan margin. Said to be produced at high elevation in the state of Mexico.
Pepos obtained from Blas Lucano Diaz. Planted with maize in early May. N.V. Tamalajota.
Pepos obtained from Sr. Juan Bailon, Avenida Revolucion
Seeds small, white with tan margin.
Two fruits flask-shaped with waxy dark green rind.
Single fruit large, club-shaped with tan rind and bright orange flesh.
Fruits tan, dark-tan mottled, necked pyriform, 15.4cm long, 15cm diam. Local  name Calabaza criolla.
Fruits diverse in shape. Sown in July, harvested in October and November. Cook mature flesh as a sweet, toast and eat seeds. Sample donated by Manuel Pina Corrales.
Fruits acorn/heart to scallop shape, ribbed, 9-10cm long, 16.5-28cm wide. Rind hard. Flesh orange, 4-5cm thick. Immature fruits cut up and fried. Seeds of mature fruit eaten. Used for dulce.

Plants had few fruits due to animal consumption of plants. Sown in July, harvested in October and November. Cook mature fruits. Powdery mildew present. Virus caused yellow streaks in fruit and vegetative parts. Sample donated by Lorenzo Gastelum Mazo.

Fruit clavate with long neck 10-47cm long, 8-13cm long, green mottlings and broken stripes with or without waxy bloom. Flesh sweet and orange. Rind soft to moderately hard. Seeds partly or readily separate from flesh.
Fruits diverse in shape. Sown in July, harvested in October and November. Cook mature flesh as a sweet, toast and eat seeds. Sample donated by Manuel Pina Corrales.
Sown in June and July, harvested in October and November. Cook mature fruit as a sweet.
Plants mature later, are less predictable and require better soil than Cucurbita mixta. Sown in June and July, harvested in November. Cook mature fruits. Sample donated by Encornacion Torres Legarra.
Fruit dark green, flask-shaped. Seeds white with tan margin. Favored variety for flesh quality.
Fruits oblate, green with yellow spots
Fruits round-flattened, small, salmon, flesh bright-orange; common
Probably similar to 'Butternut' in color, but larger and very variable in shape.
Fruit top-shape, whitish with tan, 26cm wide, 20cm long.
fruit depressed globose, ribbed, dark orange-brown, 28cm in diameter.
Fruits flattened-globose. Rind tan and green. Flesh dark orange. Local name  Abobora.
Fruits elongated. Rind cream-color. Flesh bright orange. Local name Abobora.
Seeds small, dirty white, margins lighter. Local name Zapallito anguito (Butternut).
Plants grown by Manjuy Indians for centuries, endemic. Seeds banana type, buff-colored.
Sown October, harvested April. Fruits whitish. Local name Fere.
Sown October, harvested April. Plants associated with Cucumis. Local name Mkoko.
Sown November, harvested April. Fruits creamy yellow. Local name Mhengere.
Sown November, harvested October. Local name Ndodo.
Fruits large, round, green and yellow striped.
Fruits flat and fluted. Flesh white. Local name Nboko.
Fruits large, oval creamy yellow skinned types and green striped types.
Sown November, harvested April. Fruits mixture of spotted green speckled and white brownish types.
Originally a mixed collection with TGR 1243 (PI 482478)
Sown November, harvested April. Local name Nzunzu.
Sown November, harvested April. Fruits white.
Sown November, harvested April. Fruits oval, angular to penduncle shaped, green  to yellow.
Fruit pulp and embryo's cooked for sauce. Flowers 4cm long, 2cm in diameter, yellow. Fruit roundish, 12cm long, 11cm in diameter.
Originally a mixed collection with ZFA 3633 (PI 494842)
Fruit large. Received as Cucurbita moschata.
Collected by H. Sardi and J. Jaramillo. Local name Colombian black squash.

Fruit elongated, pear shaped, 40cm long, 13cm max. diam., very slightly ribbed. Color dark green with flesh-colored spots and speckles. Flesh stringy, orange. Seeds off-white with tan border. Grown locally, purchased in store.

Elongate squash, 50cm long, 8cm diam., slightly twisted, slightly ribbed. Color light green variegated with yellow, turning mostly yellow when ripe. Peduncle woody, ribbed, flared at insertion. Flesh thick, firm, light orange. Seeds light brown, 1cm long. Ovary only in distal half of fruit, proximal half solid. Grown locally.

Fruit globose with an exceptionally long neck (13in), 22in in length; rind gold buff with splashes of paler gold, faintly ribbed; flesh orange, sweet, and tender; seed cavity heart-shaped, 5 by 8in, an excellent variety
Presented by Frank Pellet, Pellet Gardens, Atlantic, Iowa, in 1949
Fruit ovate to round, 15.2-30.5cm diameter, green with greenish-yellow blotches. Flesh 2.5-5.1cm thick, orange.
A direct descendent from the original cultivar Butternut. Unstable for butternut type fruit. Must be rogued at flowering by examination of ovary shape

Info. from Asgrow cat. No. 19 (1957) -- (NSSL application shows notation of "obsolete"). Length in inches - 10-18. Dia. in inches - 13. 120 days. Widely used for canning and suitable for stock feed. Fruits variable in shape, but usually deeper than they are wide, tapered at ends, 10-15 lb. Rind smooth, dull orange-yellow, distinctly sutured, thin, hard. Flesh thick, coarse, deep yellow, sweet.
Variety which spontaneoulsy gave rise to the first butternut-type squash. Only recorded instance of spontaneous change from crookneck to butternut fruit

Part of isogenic set derived from hand pollinator of 2 branches of a rare dimorphic plant in a field of Ponca Butternut. Produces mostly Crookneck type fruit. Only crookneck line that produces dimorphic and Crookneck F1 progeny when used to pollinate a stable butternut cultivar
Crookneck line derived from the self progeny of a rouge crookneck plant in a population of the unstable cultivar Butternut

Info. from Corneli cat. No. 14 -- 110 days. Uses - Home, market and canning. Derives name from the cheese box shape of fruits. Fruit 7" deep, 15 inches in dia., sometimes larger. Weigh 12 to 15 lbs. Very flat shape, slightly grooved. Shell hard. Skin deep yellow. Flesh fairly thick, of fine quality and flavor. Orange-yellow.
Part of isogenic set derived from hand pollinator of 2 branches of a rare dimorphic plant in a field of Ponca Butternut. Relatively stable producer of butternut type fruit
Large butternut, thick neck, sometimes dumb-bell shape.  Tan skin, bright orange flesh; rather late.
